<Base title="ai-radar — live demo — Andrew Yang">
  <h1>ai-radar: reliability semantics you can audit</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    A queue-based pipeline that collects AI news from multiple sources, digests it
    with an LLM, and publishes a daily static digest — plus a dashboard of the
    system's own health. The content is the by-product; the system is the point.
  </p>

  <h2>What it demonstrates</h2>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li>
      <strong>At-least-once delivery, idempotent consumers:</strong> manual ack after
      the database commit; every side effect keyed on a unique constraint; state-machine
      transitions make redelivery a no-op.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A TTL + DLX retry ladder</strong> (30s / 5m / 1h wait-queues, no plugins)
      with a dead-letter queue, a <code>replay</code> CLI, and a triage runbook.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>An LLM cost circuit breaker:</strong> when the daily budget is spent the
      consumer stops and the backlog waits <em>in the queue</em> for the next window —
      the clearest argument for a broker over a cron job.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Honest architecture decisions:</strong> eight ADRs, including why a
      message broker at all (and where the cron-job line is), and why docker-compose
      rather than Kubernetes for a single-host system.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Links</h2>
  <p>
    <a href="https://github.com/nplus-father/ai-radar">Source &amp; ADRs on GitHub</a><br />
    <span class="muted">Live dashboard: coming online with the site repo — the data
    source (hourly pipeline-health snapshots) is already being captured.</span>
  </p>
</Base>
